          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d201873a-db72-408c-b29c-c2be0972d39b",
        "score": 0.4882077,
        "text": "The document is from the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement Electronic Tariff, specifically Section 40, dated February 5, 2025. It outlines the process for Distributed Generation Facilities (DGFs) with active interconnection requests to obtain Deliverability Status. Key points include:\n\n1. **Queue Position**: DGFs must follow the interconnection queue of the applicable IOU Participating Transmission Owner as per Section 40.4.6.3.2.2.1.\n\n2. **Insufficient Potential DGD**: If there is not enough Potential Deliverable Generation Deliverability (DGD) at a Node, DGFs are prioritized by queue position. If multiple DGFs share the same position, they are prioritized by expected Commercial Operation date.\n\n3. **Pro Rata Share**: If DGFs have the same expected Commercial Operation date, they receive a pro rata share of the remaining Potential DGD based on expected MW energy production.\n\n4. **Utilization of Potential DGD**: IOU Participating Transmission Owners must fully utilize the available Potential DGD at each Node. Excess Potential DGD is treated as unassigned if the total MW of eligible DGFs is less than the available Potential DGD.\n\nThis process ensures fair allocation of deliverability status to DGFs based on queue position and expected operation dates.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_1073.jpg",
          "page_num": 1073,
